    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1843-05-08_page01.jpg"/>
                
                <opener>
                    
                    <date when="1843-05-08">May 8, 1843</date>
                </opener>
                <p>
                Trim Monday 8<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> . 1843<lb/>
                <note>74</note><lb/>
                My dearest <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">mother</persName> ,<lb/>
                I am steady and true to my<lb/>
                promise about the week and<lb/>
                remember I said I would not<lb/>
                pin myself to the day - <choice> 
                <orig>There=<lb/>
                fore</orig>
                <reg>Therefore</reg>
                </choice>
                though I at first said<lb/>
                Thursday I now say Saturday<lb/>
                next if you please - the 13<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> -<lb/>
                I will be at home to dinner<lb/></p>
                
                <p>
                - My dear you cannot come<lb/>
                to meet me unless you were<lb/>
                to ride one of the coach horses<lb/>
                which I think would be <choice> 
                <orig>un-<lb/>
                seemly</orig>
                <reg>unseemly</reg>
                </choice><lb/>
                and rather <choice> 
                <orig>uncom<lb/>
                fortably</orig>
                <reg>uncomfortably</reg>
                </choice><lb/>
                - you know that I<lb/>
                come home in your carriage<lb/>
                so I want only horses - If<lb/>
                yours are in good trim and<lb/>
                peculiarly engaged on <choice> 
                <orig>Satur<lb/>
                day</orig>
                <reg>Saturday</reg>
                </choice>
                next you will be so good<lb/>
                as to send them to meet me at<lb/>
                <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Mullingar_IE">Mullingar</placeName> - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH2">Harriet</persName> who is<lb/>
                
                <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1843-05-08_page02.jpg"/>
                always kinder than one can<lb/>
                conceive or invent, has contrived<lb/>
                for herself how she can give me<lb/>
                the pleasure of her company to<lb/>
                <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Mullingar_IE">Mullingar</placeName> and can return<lb/>
                without the chaise which carries<lb/>
                us there - She will never<lb/>
                heeding the <unclear>ignoming</unclear> return<lb/>
                on a jaunt - or jaunting car<lb/>
                which she assures me she thinks<lb/>
                a delightful vehicle - See the<lb/>
                magic of that dearest of Faeries<lb/>
                Goodwill which can convert<lb/>
                the worst into the best! and <choice> 
                <orig>al<lb/>
                ways</orig>
                <reg>always</reg>
                </choice>
                prove herself a gainer<lb/>
                by the bargain<lb/></p>
                
                <p>
                You hear I am quite well<lb/>
                and happy and you shall<lb/>
                see the same on Saturday -<lb/>
                Love I will send to nobody<lb/>
                But will bring for everybody<lb/>
                on Saturday from all here<lb/></p>
                <closer>
                 ever affectionately yours<lb/>
                 to command but never to obey Maria E<lb/>
                </closer>
                
                <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1843-05-08_page03.jpg"/>
                <postscript> 
                <p>
                <note>75</note> <lb/>
                I forgot my dear mother where<lb/>
                I said about Trysting place &amp;<lb/>
                that Maria <del>we</del> had your<lb/>
                chaise here, &amp; when I said about<lb/>
                the jaunt I still thought of<lb/>
                your meeting at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Mullingar_IE">Mullingar</placeName><lb/>
                - but I should not like to leave<lb/>
                her for that last 12 miles &amp; so<lb/>
                will go on home with her &amp;<lb/>
                return <choice> <orig>p Coach</orig> <reg>post coach</reg> </choice> . Or suppose -<lb/>
                suppose - that <hi rend="underline">you</hi> - I would<lb/>
                not trust her out of my hand to<lb/>
                any one else's - she caught cold<lb/>
                her last going home - could come<lb/>
                &amp; take her -? - It is too much<lb/>
                care to suppose I fear after your<lb/>
                generous deed before - so it may<lb/>
                be as aforsaid -<lb/>
                </p> </postscript> 
                
            </div>
        </body>
